<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-013-163 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 472 888</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 11 1991 v25 n45 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Advocacy group pushes for shift in Randamp;D funding. (ComputerProfessionals for Social Responsibility, federal research anddevelopment funding)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An advocacy group called the Computer Professionals for SocialResponsibility (APSR) will initiate a two-year '21st CenturyProject' plan to define how US technology policy can be reorientedto address national needs now that the Cold War is over.andP;  CPSR,which is completing fund-raising efforts and has received a$100,000 grant from the Rockefeller Foundation, is concerned thatthe impending massive reduction to the US defense budget will alsomean a corresponding plummeting in US research and development(Randamp;D) expenditures, which have been closely allied to defense.andO;The Project will consider how Randamp;D funds can be used to developsolutions for low US productivity, technical education and thedearth of technicians who fall between blue-collar workers andhigh-tech professionals.andP;  Three basic areas are to be targeted:quality of computer-related work, for example regarding ergonomicsand computer interface design; how to involve more citizens innetworking so that access to Internet and the forthcoming NationalResearch Education Network is enhanced; and technologymanufacturing methods that are non-polluting.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Professionals for Social ResponsibilityResearch and DevelopmentGovernment FundingNational GovernmentBusiness PlanningHigh Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>